            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="154" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.00/11–2845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-28">November 28,
                            1945</date>.<lb/>[Received November 29—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1367. From Amb Grady.<note n="57" xml:id="d154fn57">Ambassador Henry F. Grady had
                        arrived in Athens on November 27, accompanied by two of the ranking officers
                        of the United States contingent of the Allied Mission: Maj. Gen. Harry J.
                        Malony, U.S. Army, commanding officer of the American military component,
                        and Foy D. Kohler, Secretary General.</note> Issued following statement Grk
                    press today.</p>
                <pb facs="0197" n="185" xml:id="pg_185"/>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>The President and the SecState have asked me to come to Greece, in response
                        to the invitation of the Grk Govt, to join with other Allied reps in
                        observing the forthcoming elections in this country.</p>
                    <p>It is a mission which I have been glad to undertake. We Americans have every
                        confidence in the devotion of the Grk people to the ideals of liberty and
                        democracy. We have also a keen sense of our responsibility to help them
                        restore their sorely tried nation to political and economic health and well
                        being.</p>
                    <p>It is for the Grk people to decide what kind of govt they want. I hope that
                        our presence here will help reassure them that they can do so freely and
                        fairly and without fear.</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <list>
                            <item>[Grady]</item>
                            <item>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
